.TH bluraybackup-ex 1 "March 2026" "bluraybackup-ex 2.2.0"
.SH NAME
bluraybackup-ex \- backup Blu-ray Disc Movies using libbluray
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bluraybackup-ex
.B extract
[-k \fIkeyfile\fR] [-b \fIsize\fR] \fIsource\fR \fIoutput-dir\fR

.B bluraybackup-ex
.B patch
[-k \fIkeyfile\fR] [-b \fIsize\fR] \fIsource.iso\fR \fIoutput.iso\fR

.B bluraybackup-ex
.B check
[-k \fIkeyfile\fR] [-b \fIsize\fR] \fIsource\fR

.B bluraybackup-ex
{-h | --help | -v | --version}
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBbluraybackup-ex\fP makes a decrypted copy of a Blu-ray Disc Movie
from a physical drive, an ISO/BIN disc image, or a directory
containing a BDMV structure.

Three subcommands are provided:
.IP \fBextract\fP 8
Extract the full disc file tree into \fIoutput-dir\fB/<disc-label>\fR/.
.IP \fBpatch\fP 8
Produce a single decrypted ISO image.
Phase\~1 copies every sector of the source image verbatim;
Phase\~2 overwrites all encrypted .m2ts streams with AACS-decrypted
content obtained via libbluray.
The source must be a regular ISO/BIN file.
.IP \fBcheck\fP 8
Read every file on the disc to verify readability.
On AACS-encrypted discs each 6144-byte unit MAC is validated and
failed blocks are reported with their file path and byte offset.
.PP
To read protected Blu-ray media you need \fBlibaacs\fR installed and a
valid \fBKEYDB.cfg\fR file. Some discs also require \fBlibbdplus\fR.
.SH OPTIONS
The following options are accepted by all subcommands.
.TP
\fB-k\fR, \fB--keydb\fR=\fIFILE\fR
Use the specified AACS keys database file.
If omitted, \fBbluraybackup-ex\fR searches the standard locations and
common filename variants (see
.B KEYDB SEARCH PATH
below).
.TP
\fB-b\fR, \fB--buffer\fR=\fISIZE\fR
Set the I/O buffer size. Accepted suffixes: \fBk\fR/\fBK\fR (×1024),
\fBm\fR/\fBM\fR (×1024²), \fBg\fR/\fBG\fR (×1024³), or plain bytes.
Must be at least 6144 (one AACS unit, 3 BD sectors).
Default: \fB6144\fR. Larger values (e.g. \fB6m\fR) significantly
improve throughput on ISO images and SSDs.
.TP
\fB-h\fR, \fB--help\fR
Print usage information.
With no subcommand, print global help.
With a subcommand, print subcommand-specific help.
.TP
\fB-v\fR, \fB--version\fR
Print version and license information (global flag only).
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
\fIsource\fR
Disc source for \fBextract\fR and \fBcheck\fR.
May be a physical Blu-ray device path (e.g. \fB/dev/sr0\fR),
an ISO/BIN image file, or a directory containing a BDMV structure.
.TP
\fIsource.iso\fR
Input ISO/BIN image file for \fBpatch\fR. Must be a regular file.
.TP
\fIoutput-dir\fR
Base output directory for \fBextract\fR.
The disc label is appended automatically: \fIoutput-dir\fB/<disc-label>\fR/.
.TP
\fIoutput.iso\fR
Output decrypted ISO file path for \fBpatch\fR.
.SH BEHAVIOR
.TP
Subcommand dispatch
The first non-option argument must be one of \fBextract\fR,
\fBpatch\fR, or \fBcheck\fR.
.TP
patch source requirement
\fBpatch\fR requires its \fIsource.iso\fR argument to be a regular
file. Device paths and BDMV directories are not supported.
.SH KEYDB SEARCH PATH
When \fB-k\fR is not provided, \fBbluraybackup-ex\fR searches:
.IP "Linux / macOS" 16
\fI~/.config/aacs/KEYDB.cfg\fR and filename variants
\fIkeydb.cfg\fR, \fIKeyDB.cfg\fR, \fIKEYDB.CFG\fR.
.IP Windows 16
\fI%APPDATA%\\\|aacs\\\|KEYDB.cfg\fR and the same variants.
Falls back to \fIKEYDB.cfg\fR in the current directory if the
environment variable is unset.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\fB0\fP
Operation completed successfully.
.TP
\fB1\fP
An error occurred.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Extract file tree from a physical drive
.B bluraybackup-ex extract /dev/sr0 ~/backup
.TP
Extract file tree from an ISO image
.B bluraybackup-ex extract disc.iso ~/backup
.TP
Extract with a 1 MB buffer for faster throughput
.B bluraybackup-ex extract -b 1m disc.iso /output/dir
.TP
Produce a decrypted ISO (6 MB buffer)
.B bluraybackup-ex patch -b 6m encrypted.iso decrypted.iso
.TP
Verify disc readability
.B bluraybackup-ex check /dev/sr0
.TP
Verify an ISO image
.B bluraybackup-ex check disc.iso
